.TH COREWAR 8 "12 Sep 2020" "1.0" "corewar man page"
.SH COREWAR
COREWAR
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./corewar [-dump N | -d N] [-a] [-l] [-v] [[-n N] file.cor]
.SH DESCRIPTION
COREWAR is a 1984 programming game created by D. G. Jones and A. K. Dewdney in which two or more battle programs (called "warriors") compete for control of a virtual computer. These battle programs are written in an abstract assembly language called Redcode.
.SH OPTIONS
The following options are available:
.TP
.B -n
This flag assigns an id number to the specified champion. And players who did not receive such a number using the flag, first of the unused id's will be assigned
.TP
.B -dump
At the end of nbr_cycles of executions, the program dumps the memory on the standard output
and quit the game. The memory is dumped in the hexadecimal format with
32 octets per line.
.TP
.B -d
At the end of nbr_cycles of executions, the program dumps the memory on the standard output
and quit the game. The memory is dumped in the hexadecimal format with
64 octets per line.
.TP
.B -a
Prints output from "aff" (Default is to hide it)
.TP
.B -l
For each valid execution of the live instruction, the machine display:
A process shows that player X (champion_name) is alive.
.TP
.B -v
A graphic interface for the virtual machine using nCurses.
.SH SEE ALSO
ASM(8)
.SH BUGS
No known bugs EVER. Yes you read that right.
